[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Taimanov - Najdorf, Zurich 1953"]
[Result "*"]

{ Welcome to the book!  As an introduction, we will start with probably the most famous King's Indian game of all time, after it was immortalised in Bronstein's book of the tournament.  Najdorf had lost to Gligoric a few months earlier, in the game which gave the variation its name - the 'Mar del plata variation'.  Here, in the candidates tournament, he puts the lesson to good use. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7
{ Here ....d5 would be the Grunfeld.  After White's next that option is gone and we are firmly in King's Indian territory. }
4. e4 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. Be2
{ This system, with d4, c4, Nc3, Nf3 and Be2 is the traditional main line - the classical variation.  Black is going to have to strike back in the centre, with either ...c5 , or the much more popular e5.  After ...c5, White could push with d5, producing  a type of Benoni, or keep the tension and invite ...cd, leading to a Maroczy bind.  It is rare for either of those openings to be reached by this move order. }
6... e5
{ White now has a choice: he can exchange on e5  (relatively boring)  , push on to d5 or keep the tension.  Pushing d4 - d5 straight away is perfectly respectable - the Petrosian variation.  But it is generally more effective to keep the tension for a move or two, inviting Black to make some concession in order to force White to relinquish it.  So 7 Be3  (The Gligoric variation)  , and especially 7 OO are generally regarded as more testing. }
7. O-O
{ Black can take on d4 here, but this is not a particularly favourable version of that pawn structure - a little better for White but only scores slightly worse than the main lines.  However, most King's Indian players want to provoke White into playing d5, stabilising the centre. With the centre stable they can then arrange to play ...f5 and a king's side attack.  The downside is that White will get a queenside one, usually revolving around the break c4-c5. }
7... Nc6
{ The traditional way of provoking d5.  White normally plays along.  Black is threatening Nxd4.  White could exchange with de - insipid and unpromising after either ...de or Nxe5.  More promising is the rare but dangerous 8 Be3 - though it seems like Re8! is a nice equaliser there.  After 8 Be3 Re8, White's 9 d5 can now be met by ...Nd4! without losing material. On the other hand 9 de  (the main line of 8 Be3)  de 10 Qxd8 Nxd8! looks fine for Black - the line normally continuing 11 Nb5 Ne6 12 Ng5 Re7 and White's pressure seems to be evaporating. }
8. d5
{ This leaves 8 d5!  as the main line - played in 90% of the games on my database.  As compared with 7 d5, White has gained the move OO, Black Nc6.  White is claiming that the knight on c6 will be worse placed on e7 than it would be after 7 d5 a5 and later Na6.  And he's right - e7 is a very bad square for the piece.  But not to worry, it gets moving very soon.  Firstly it zips round to g6.  From there it often eventually goes to h4, but also surprisingly common is the h8 square, wheeling round to f7 and h6 to help Black push ...g5 ->g4. }
8... Ne7
{ This key tabia is called the 'Mar del Plata' variation of the King's Indian.  Black will attack on the King's side, White on the Queen's.  White has a variety of moves here, but the three key ones all involve the break c4-c5.  The bayonet attack was very popular at the turn of the century - White plays for c5 as directly as possible, and keeps the knight on f3 to make a nuisance of itself on the King's side.  Nd2 assumes that c5 will be played soon  (probably with the help of b4)  , and prepares to put the knight on c4 afterwards - the ideal square for the piece.  It also prevents ...Nh5  (which would simply be taken)  , and prepares to meet ...f5 with f3.  Ne1, the traditional main line, is similar.  In this case, the knight usually  (though not always)  proceeds to d3 to help with the c4-c5 push.  Once c5 is played the knight is not so well placed though, so it often drops back to f2 for defensive purposes.  This is,however, not always an option... }
9. Ne1 Nd7
{ Black needs to move the knight in order to play ...f5.  He has a choice of two squares - d7 or e8.  d7 has the extra virtue of holding up c5 - it is the most popular move and scores slightly better of the two.  Ne8 though does set a nice positional trap.  The point is that in the main lines, the knight often goes to d7  (to allow ...f5)  then back to f6  (to pressure White into playing f3)  and then back to e8  (to guard the d6 pawn and c7 square)  .  Ne8 players hope that White will play f3 unprovoked, and Black can save two tempi! Many people  (including both Kasparov and your not-so-humble author)  have won some nice games with this line, with the White players often confused as to where they went wrong.  It is not all upside however.  10 Be3, nasty enough against Nd7, is meant to be even stronger against Ne8.  Second problem is that plans with f4 by White become viable  (they would be useless against Nd7 - Black would just play ...ef and plonk a knight on e5)  .  They can be defused, but it's extra stuff to know.  Worst of all though is that if White simply plays 10 Bd2 he can avoid playing f3 until Black forces him to with ...Nf6 - and we have transposed to the Nd7 lines anyway.  It was actually the last point that made me personally drop the line. }
10. Be3
{ Yet another major choice for White.  10 Nd3 is the most straightforward. While White scores well  (and Black reasonably)  in practice, in a sense the variation is quite drawish.  White gets something on the Q side, Black opens the K side - and White has enough space to zip the pieces over to the K side and neutralise the pressure. Often Black ends up with an open g file and a heavy piece or two, but a bad dark square bishop - a common problem in the classical KI.  10 Be3 on the other hand is much more critical.  White develops the piece to a much more active diagonal than d2  (where it ends up in the other line)  , supporting c5 and looking at the b6 and a7 squares beyond it.  However, the bishop itself becomes a target.  White is going to hide it on f2.  It remains an aggressive piece there, but defensively it has a dual Jekyll/Hyde nature.  In a sense it is an extra defender; on the other hand, as in this game, it is also an extra target, and it takes away the key defensive f2 square from the White knight. It is not unusual for the bishop to drop back to e1  (both here and in the Nd3/Bd2 lines)  .  B on e1, N on f2 is often a very good defensive set up.  The database statistics show the fighting nature of Be3 - compared with Nd3, White scores slightly better overall, but the position is far less drawish - 22% draws as opposed to 27%. }
10... f5
{ In the Nd3 lines White now normally plays Bd2, keeping the tension.  Only after Black plays N back to f6 does he play f3.  In that line, both players have an extra option - the e4/f5 exchange.  This results in a more static game, with White usually posting a knight on e4 and Black a knight on d4  (via f5)  .  This can be pretty irritating for Black.  His K side attack hasn't quite vanished, but it is harder to get anything really brutal in.  On the other hand White still has a Q side nibble.  It makes a difference though who makes the exchange.  Let's imagine W plays ef.  Play continues Nxf5 Ne4 Nd4 and it's White's turn again - he has reached the position 'for free'.  However, if Black plays ...fe then White simply recaptures - Nxe4 - and while it is Black's turn again he needs two more tempi for the moved N-f5-d4.  Black also has the option of meeting ef with gf. Botvinnik wrote of similar positions that 'every Russian schoolboy' knows this is the correct recapture. In the position after 10 Nd3 f5 11 ef, 11..gf is indeed more popular and scores better.  White almost always meets it with 12 f4.  Black can then keep the tension, or push on with ...e4.  e4 is popular, but a little positionally suspect.  Black doesn't have the e5 square, and there is the long term danger that White will eventually break things up with g4.  Stronger players seem to prefer keeping the tension with ....Ng6 and eventually releasing it with ...ef  In the Be3 line however, ef makes no sense at all - Nxf5 hits the bishop.  f5 is virtually always met by f3. }
11. f3
{ Black now has a choice.  Novice players are often attracted by fe, opening the f file for Black.  But after Nxe4, or the even stronger fe, Black has nothing, whikle his Q side is still vulnerable.  Instead, Black sees f3 as a weakness.  He claims his own space advantage on the King's side by pushing f5 - f4 and aiming for the break g5 - g4.  This makes it much harder for White to defend - it is tricky for him to either funnel pieces to the defence, or to evacuate his king from the danger zone.  White usually places his hopes on the Q side attack, aiming to win material there and then infiltrate behind enemy lines in a clockwise direction. }
11... f4 12. Bf2 g5 13. Nd3
{ This is where the game looks a little dated.  The modern darlings are 13 Rc1 and 13 a4  (scoring 58% and 60% respectively on my database)  .  Nd3 by contrast clocks in with a measley 43% score - still played in several hundred games, but still probably counting as a misstep by White. }
13... Nf6
{ No point having the knight on d7 now - Nd3 has made sure c5 is coming next.  Ng6 will almost certainly be played next though , so the two moves usually transpose. }
14. c5 Ng6 15. Rc1 Rf7
{ The older computers still love White here.  Stockfish 9 is more canny though, and only gives White a modest plus.  White will probably play cd soon, when Black will have two weaknesses.  Fast cars and beautiful women - all King's Indian players are honorary super secret super spies.  On the chess board though, he has a weak pawn on d6, and a potential entry point for the White pieces on c7. A rook there could be quite annoying, but more commonly the threat is to get a knight there.  On one hand this would simply threaten Nxa8.  On the other, it could go to e6.  It would be such a monster there Black would have to take it, but after Bxe6 de, Black really misses his light squared bishop  (a key attacker against White's king)  while White has the bishop pair, the d5 square, the c4-g8 diagonal and, at least temporarily a pawn on e6.  This almost always adds up to a totally winning position.  Moral:  Dont let the knight in to c7 in this line, and especially not e6.  Black has a thematic defensive/offensive maneuver to counter all of this.  He lifts the rook to f7, defending c7 and  (later)  b7, and then plays Bf-8, defending d6.  The rook is then ready to slide to g7, still defending laterally but also preparing the ...g4 break and being ideally placed for action after it is achieved.  The Bf8 usually stays there, but sometimes finds time to make itself useful - either from h6, or,  (afer cd cd)  via d7-b6.  In this game we see a pawn sacrifice that turns the normally passive dark square bishop into a monster.  But for now, simply remember the key Rf7, Bf8, Rg7 maneuver. }
16. Rc2
{ A normal move, but in this position very rare.  White normally plays cd, after which he scores an impressive 30%.  He does however have a sneaky alternative in Kh1, with the idea of Rg1!  Interested parties can check out Marin's video on chessbase or turn on their engines... }
16... Bf8 17. cxd6 cxd6
{ We are now down to three games in my database, and despite the computers still giving White the slight nod, it's not clear that he is theoretically even still ok.  He has delayed  the cd move a little too long, and put too much emphasis on creating pressure on the c file as opposed to hopping forward with his knight to b5. }
18. Qd2
{ This though is a fairly clear mistake.  Doubling the rooks on the c file is nice, but the queen move takes the pressure off g4, allowing Black to get this key break in straight away.  Black is clearly better here. }
18... g4 19. Rfc1
{ So, g4 achieved - what next?  Often the answer is gf, with pressure on the g  (and sometimes h)  files.  This can in turn sometimes be followed by a sac on e4, freeing the f3 pawn.  There is a more common follow up however - g4- g3. Here, this sacrifices a pawn but Black gets tremendous compensation.  Without the bishop on f2 though it is still very much a standard idea - White usually meets it with h3, blocking the king side - and Black sacrifices his bishop on h3, unblocking it again.  May require another piece sca or two and a bit of calculation, but this is usually curtains for White.  White has another defensive try - Kh1 followed by Bg1.  The main drawback here is Black's plan of sacrificing a knight on g3.  All very nasty. }
19... g3 20. hxg3 fxg3 21. Bxg3 Nh5
{ The standard follow up.  In return for the pawn Black has the g file, the f4 and g3 squares and indeed most of the dark squares in general.  Where should the White bishop go?  Stockfish 9 slightly prefers f2; but Taimanov tries to keep some control of f4 and g3 - a very human move. }
22. Bh2
{ Hard to tell whether this is the losing move, or whether White was already lost.  He certainly seems to be losing after this move. }
22... Be7
{ It is very tempting to just try to get something going with the Queen, rook and pair of knights. But this is even better.  The bishop is going to e3 - where he'd be better described as a Pope! }
23. Nb1
{ Sad.  This knight's rightful trajectory was to b5. But since Black is going to have to play Bd7 anyway, the knight would just look silly there, and after Nb5 Bd7 a4 Bg5 Black wins the exchange. }
23... Bd7
{ Bg5 would be great - except that it loses instantly to Rxc8.  So Black has to take time out to play Bd7 -but this is a handy little move anyway. }
24. Qe1
{ White avoids losing the exchange - but by now the lesser evil was simply parting with it:  24 Bf1 Bg5 25 Qe1 Bxc1  26 Qxc1 Ngf4 27 Rc7 - and while White is still getting crushed, you could just about call it a fight. }
24... Bg5
{ Instead of Bg5, Stockfish finds a nice tickle -Bh4, aiming for g3. I suppose it is a question of which you find more scary - a Pope, or a bishop heading up an inquisition... }
25. Nd2 Be3+ 26. Kh1
{ Trash talking is of course forbidden in serious tournament chess, but if you can mutter 'Back in your box, dog boy' it usually means that things are going rather well. }
26... Qg5 { As mentioned, Black owns the dark squares. } 27. Bf1
{ Rd1 was apparently the best grovel. } 27... Raf8
{ A nice, human, winning, 'get the last piece into play' move.  But White can still try an exchange sac with Nc4, so ruling this out with ...b5 first was probably technically stronger. }
28. Rd1 { White wants Nc4 without dropping the exchange. } 28... b5
{ Black cuts it out.  White is totally tied up and losing.  Still, it seems to have been even stronger to simply allow Nc4 here. 28...Nh4! - and if 29 Nc4 Bd4 Nxd6?! then Rf6! is crushing.  Skeptics may turn on their engines : }
29. a4 { Queenside play!  'Yay' !  Rc7 was a better grovel. } 29... a6
{ And here again, a6 , keeping the clamp is a nice human move, but ...Nh4!  was a computer powered splat.  A Black advantage of around one and a half v five pawns in 'computer speak'  . }
30. axb5 axb5 31. Rc7
{ Rc6 a better try - Stockfish 9 calls this around +1 for Black, whereas Rc7 is '+2'. }
31... Rg7 32. Nb3
{ A blunder in a losing position. Many moves were better here - perhaps b4 was best?  The evaluation now jumps to over +6. }
32... Nh4 33. Rc2
{ I initially set my computer to analyse this game at the rate of 5 minutes per move.  After Rc2 it rebelled and thought for 164 minutes, and announced mate in 63.  Make of that what you will! }
33... Bh3 34. Qe2 { 34 Rdd2 Bxf3 is slightly 'better'. } 34... Nxg2
{ A very human combination.  Open the g file, swap on g2 a few times, and when the Queen ends up there, side step with the Black Queen and the W Queen has no good squares.  The ruthless computer though sees Nxf3, and claims mate in 11 - rather more plausible than its last one. Nxh2 and Ng3+ are both huge threats. }
35. Bxg2 Bxg2+ 36. Qxg2 Qh4 37. Qxg7+
{ It is an amusing exercise to look at each alternate Queen retreat and see how it drops off. }
37... Kxg7 38. Rg2+ Kh8 39. Ne1 { 'Mate in 21'.  Nd2 is just '-11'. } 39... Nf4
40. Rg3 { Nd2 is mate in 20 - this is mate in 11. } 40... Bf2
{ ... providing Black had started with Rf6.  Mate in 21 now apparently, but all nitpicking of course - Black is totally winning.  Still, it can be interesting to play with these positions and look at them through a computer's eyes. }
41. Rg4 { Ng2!  (Shrug)  . } 41... Qh3 42. Nd2 h5 43. Rg5
{ The best move.  Black can win a piece now with Qh4, or he can play Rg8 and mate in 7.  But whether because of the clock or resignation, he never had to make that decision.  A very impressive game, given how early it was in the variation's history, and full of ideas still in use today. }
