[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Fianchetto Variation"]
[Black "Pachman - Bronstein, Prague 1946."]
[Result "*"]

{ Bronstein played two very famous games in 1946, crunching up the fianchetto variation.  This was the earlier of the two. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 d6
{ Bronstein enters the line via an Old Indian move order.  Indeed, the King's Indian really grew out of the Old Indian - in that opening you often have to take on d4, and it struck people that under those circumstances the dark square bishop would be much more actively placed on g7.  Ironically, in a lot of modern variations, the dark square bishop isn't active at all - the position closes and it becomes a problem piece.  But it still played its role, firstly in encouraging White to close the position, and secondly in making sure he is careful about how he opens it again.  In the fianchetto variation in particular though White often keeps the position fluid for much longer than he normally does in other lines, so the bishop has more of a chance to shine.  In the Bronstein games we are going to see, its glorious destiny is to exchange itself off for a knight... }
3. Nc3 e5
{ Bronstein is happy to allow  4.dxe5  dxe5  5.Qxd8  Kxd8  and Pachman wisely declines. My database has over a thousand examples of that position, with White scoring 37%. It is not so much that it is actually bad for White, just not at all better - and it can take some time before White realises this. }
4. Nf3 Nbd7
{ 4...e4  would have been playable, but not particularly good;  5.Nd2!  (rather than)  Ng5!?  (looks like an advantage for White.) }
5. g3
{ 5.e4  would be very respectable of course, but in these two games the players go for the fianchetto variation. Even then it was recognised as pretty unpleasant for Black.  Black's move order has committed him to defending with a Nbd7 defence; other lines based on ...Nc6, ...a6 and ...b5, ...c5, or ...c6 and ...Qa5 have been ruled out.  Nbd7 lines are hard to handle - White scores well - but they are in a sense the most aggressive.  A lot of pieces stay on, and play is fluid. }
5... g6 6. Bg2 Bg7 7. O-O O-O 8. b3
{ The most common line these days is 8. e4 followed by 9. h3.  But 8. e4 and 9. b3  (which we reach by transposition)  is also very nasty. }
8... Re8
{ It is interesting to compare the following sequence with the Zita game.  Bronstein plays all the same moves, but in a different order.  In the first game, against Pachman, he is very straightforward.  Rook to e8, open the e- file, increase pressure on the e- pawn with Nc5, and then a5- a4.  Only then does he play ...c6 and ...Qb6.  In both games he plays ...axb3 after White plays Ba1  .  In the second, against Zita, he is more cagey.  The modern looking ...c6 comes first, followed by Re8, and then he huddles up into a little 3rd rank ball:  ..exd4 and Qb6 come next.  Only then does he expand - Nc5, a5-a4 xb3 etc.  White also plays almost all the same moves  (though in tactically relevant orders)  .  The exception is that Zita plays the move Qd2, while Pachman plays h3.  Which Black move order is better?  Well, starting with Re8 looks right; but after that they have their pros and cons.  In modern play   9.e4  c6  is often met by  10.h3  , and Black scores very badly.  Most strong modern players seem to prefer   9.e4  exd4  , though this runs into issues with  10.Nxd4  Nc5  11.f3!  If pressed, I'd go the Pachman route  (early exd4)  against an early b3, but in general, ...c6 and keeping the tension for a while works better in most lines. }
9. e4 exd4 10. Nxd4 Nc5 11. Re1
{ A very natural move, and can't be bad, but in modern play   11.f3!  scores well, while  Re1  scores badly. Against this, Black should probably play  11...c6  , after which we see another modern treatment: White develops his bishop not to  b2  (, but to)  e3  .  12.Be3!  leaves Black with a choice; sometimes he presses on with  12... a5  (; Nakamura once beat Kramnik with)  12... Qe7  (.  The move he'd like to play)  (and frequently does play)  is  12...d5!?  But this is a pawn sacrifice:  13.Nxc6!  bxc6  14.Bxc5  leaves Black looking for compensation. In Master play the games seem to have all continued  14...dxc4?!  but  15.f4!  looks quite good for White. Black is perhaps better off playing  14... Be6  (, with some, but not full compensation for the pawn.) }
11... a5
{ The reason 11. Re1 has fallen out of favour is because Black has an immediate shot here.   11...Ng4!.  Always been on the lookout for this move when  h3  hasn't been played. The engine Leela then immediately wants a draw with  12.Bf4  Ne5  13.Be3  Ng4  14.Bf4.  Instead, a typical sequence in Master play is   11...Ng4  12.f3  Ne5  Qf6  (is interesting here as well)  13.Be3  f5!?.  Silly humans! Black scores extremely well here  (over 80%)  (, though)  13...c6  may actually be a better move.  Play trundles on with  14.Qd2  fxe4  15.Bg5  Qd7  16.Nxe4  Nxe4  17.Rxe4??  (silly humans!)  Nf7!  and Black wins. The White queen is overloaded guarding the 2 minor pieces, and Black ends up winning one of them, even after  18.Rxe8  Qxe8  19.f4  (or)  Re1 Bxd4+  c5.  Among other games, see Larsen - Stein, Belgrade 1970 - though Stein played  17... Nc6  , and Nikolic - Gulko, Hastings 1990.   As a side note,  11...c6  also has a crushing score for Black here, though White should have his typical  (large)  edge if he finds the accurate  12.h3!  rather than the superficially attractive  12.Bb2. }
12. Bb2
{ This was the plan.  The old plan.  The natural plan. I wouldn't actually call it a  bad  plan - but only because I like seeing Black victories.   (Once again, Black has missed his chance for)  12...Ng4   , and White should take it away from him with  12.h3!.  And when he develops his bishop, it should probably go to  e3  (rather than)  b2  . It may look attractive to have the latent threat of swapping Black's fianchettoed bishop off, but White is actually quite shaky on the dark squares and he should prefer to keep those pieces on. Of course, it took a bit of experience before even master level players realised this, and the King's Indian was very fresh in the 40s. Black should probably continue  12...c6  , but after  13.Rb1!  (or)  Bf4  (White is better.) }
12... a4
{ Lots of things are good now.   12...c6  is played most often, and reaches a common position where Black scores over 70%  .   12...h5  is good.   Bronstein's  12...a4  is also good, with theoretical equality but a large plus score the in the few games this position was reached. }
13. Rc1 { Other games have continued  13.Rb1  or   13.b4  here. } 13... c6
{ Bronstein over finesses here. White should jump at the chance to play  14.b4!   Of course,  13...axb3  14.axb3  was correct, and then our old friend  14...Ng4!  15.Rb1  and only now  15...c6  - with a nice Black edge. Kasparov's  15. Rc2 is also met not by Ne5, but again c6, with an edge. }
14. Ba1 axb3 { Better late than never! } 15. axb3 Qb6
{ Not bad, but  15...Ng4!  or  15...Nfd7!  are splatzen,     After  15...Ng4!  , White can limp on with  16.Na4  - Not  Rb1 Qf6!  --/+ -  Nxa4  17.bxa4  , while   After  15...Nfd7!  play continues  16.Rb1  Ne5  17.Rf1  h5  18.h3  Ned3  and Black is swarming into the White position.   Bronstein was a tactical genius, but he missed a lot of tact - tickles! }
16. h3
{ Pachman cottons onto the importance of the g4 square first, though the multiple inaccuracies on either side have resulted in a position where Black happens to be clearly better anyway.    What now?  16...Nh5  isn't dumb, putting the knight on an active square and at least temporarily holding up  f4.  But Bronstein's move is probably better, aiming at the  e5  (square.) }
16... Nfd7 17. Rb1
{ White probably needs to guard the b- pawn again now the knight on d4 is under attack, though actually winning it with Bxd4 would be risky given the counter attack on the long diagonal. }
17... Nf8
{ This on the other hand is lame, and the horse stays here for the rest of the game.    It looks as if  17...Ne5!?  gets immediately hit by  18.f4  - but this blunders  Rxa1!!  19.Rxa1  Ned3  and White is crunched.   So White has to meet  17...Ne5!?  with  18.Re3  , and a Black edge.   But best was  17...h5!  18.Re3  (still probably best)  Bh6!  19.Re1  and now Black can jump in with  Ne5!  or repeat moves with  19... Bg7 20. Re3 h4  (, softening up the kingside.) }
18. Kh2
{ So, White has been handed equality again.  How to consolidate?  Not like this!    18.Re3!  was best guarding  f3, d3, c3 and b3  . Black could start asking questions on the king side with  18...h5  , and possibly follow up with  Qd8     18.Na4  , sacrificing the pawn structure to reduce some of the pressure also made sense, though it is clearly better for Black and White would have needed to have decided that he already needed to take emergency measures. }
18... h5 { Not bad, but  18...Rxa1!  is already on. } 19. Re2
{ Almost consolidating.... but not quite.  19.Re3!  leaves Black better after  h4!  20.gxh4!  (g4?! Nfe6 -/+)  Qd8!  21.Nf3  Nfe6  22.Na4!  , but White's position is surprisingly close to OK, all things considered. }
19... h4
{ 19...Rxa1?!  doesn't do much here, though Black is still a a little better after  20.Rxa1  Nfe6. }
20. Rd2
{ But it does now! After  20...Rxa1  21.Rxa1  Bxd4  , White now has to recapture with his rook rather than his queen, so  22.Rxd4  Nxb3  is then possible. So... }
20... Rxa1 21. Rxa1 Bxd4 22. Rxd4 Nxb3
{ You can think of this tactic in the simplest terms like this.  Black sacrifices the exchange, and then bishop for knight, in order to attract the White rooks to squares that make Nxb3 a fork, winning the exchange back and winning a pawn in the process.  That pawn is immediately lost again  Rxd6  , but the operation is a success for Black as he has swapped off his weak d6 pawn, while the remaining White c- pawn is weak.    However, looking a little deeper, winning back the exchange rebounds on Black:  23.Rxd6  Nxa1?  24.Nd5!  (using the lateral pin)  Qxf2  25.Nf6+  Kh8  26.Nxe8.  But even this is a bit better for Black after  26...hxg3+  27.Kh1  Nb3.  Searching for alternatives, we see things are much better for Black than this.  Instead of winning the exchange back, he can win another pawn instead.  Or two.  Or three. }
23. Rxd6 { Black is winning, but for what it is worth,  23.Rd2  is better. }
23... Qxf2
{ 'That's a mighty nice kingside you've got there.  It would be a shame if anything were to ... happen to it.' }
24. Ra2 Qxg3+ { Stuff happens to it. } 25. Kh1 Qxc3 26. Ra3 Bxh3 27. Rxb3 Bxg2+
28. Kxg2 Qxc4 29. Rd4 Qe6 30. Rxb7
{ Moves 25 - 29 have been best play by both sides, but here a computer would prefer Qf3 to the pawn grab.  Still, a dying man can eat anything... }
30... Ra8 31. Qe2 h3+
{ Pachman lost here. It would be interesting to see how Bronstein would have put him away if he had chosen to play on. The computers find something typically computery:  32.Kg1  Ra3!  33.Rd1  Re3!  34.Qxe3  Qg4+  35.Kf2  Qg2+!!  36.Ke1  h2  - but it is obvious that even with decent human play, the White king shouldn't last very long.  The whole game is a testament to the power of the knight on f8, and his magnificent display of 'Keeping out of the way and letting everybody else do all the work'.  An inspiration to us all, and a wonderful example of how life imitates chess.  But he did stop back rank checks though.  And that's important.  Ask him.  He'd tell you. }
*

