[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Fianchetto Variation"]
[Black "Botvinnik - Smyslov World Ch. Moscow 1954 game 14"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 O-O 5. Nc3 d6 6. Nf3 Nbd7 7. O-O e5 8. e4
c6
{ A standard tabia in the fianchetto line. Black takes control of d5 and b5, and gives his queen a route to b6 or a5.  White now usually plays 9 h3  (though 9 b3 is also reasonably common, and venomous)  .  After 9 h3, Qb6 is currently thought to be the critical try.  Botvinnik's Be3 is an attempt to save a tempo on h3, and is actually perfectly reasonable, though rarely played because of the following forcing line. Smyslov had analysed it before the match, and come up with the strong move 11...ed! }
9. Be3
{ Botvinnik reverted to the usual 9 h3 in the 24th match game and kept an advantage for a while.  Later, in the 1958 rematch, Smyslov met 9 h3 with the slightly dodgy Ne8, and although he got away with it he largely stopped playing the King's Indian after that. }
9... Ng4 { Obviously, the critical way to exploit the absence of h3. } 10. Bg5
{ As in almost all lines of the King's Indian, the dark square bishop is a key piece, and has to move again. Allowing Nxe3 would be at least very comfortable for Black  (read: positional catastrophe)  . }
10... Qb6
{ f6 isn't bad, and has been played by some strong players.  But this is the fun line! }
11. h3 exd4
{ Smyslov's  key idea.  In a timid mood, he could have opted for Ngf6, with a normalish looking position, a bit better for White. }
12. Na4 Qa6
{ Black actually has a pretty lousy score here on my database - only 26%!  His idea is sound, but he needs to follow up accurately. }
13. hxg4 b5 14. Nxd4
{ This natural looking move is very rare.  Much more common have been 14 Be7 and 14 c5.  14 Be7 Re8  15 Bxd6 ba  and now Smyslov gives Nxd4 Ne5, but instead 16 c5! is strong.  Black should probably try 16...d3, as 16 ... Rxe4? 17 Re1 is just bad for him.  Meanwhile, Yusupov tried 16 e5 against Kasparov.  Kasparov calls his reply, ...c5 "holding the balance", but the computer thinks he already has the edge, and he went on to win.  The computer also likes e5 Qxc4.  The first game I can find with 14 c5 was played in 1996.  It was later used in 2005 in a clash of the theoreticians, Avrukh v Kotronias.  Avrukh won, but after 14 ... ba 15 cd, Black should be equal after 15 ...c5, and may even be slightly better after 15...Rb8  Botvinnik actually mentioned 14 c5 in his notes, but rejected it due to 14...dc  15 Nxc5 Nxc5 16 Be7 Ne6! }
14... bxa4 15. Nxc6
{ 'In this way White wins the exchange, but subjects himself to considerable danger' - Smyslov.  Instead 15 Be7 Re8   16 Bxd6 Ne5 and Black is fine.  The only other example I can find is someone trying it in correspondence play in 1997.  White also got stomped in that game too.  Kasparov mentions the unclear 15 b3 Ne5 in "Great Predecessors" }
15... Qxc6 16. e5 Qxc4 17. Bxa8 Nxe5
{ Black has a pawn for the exchange, and some play against White's king.  In the 97 game, White grabbed the d6 pawn here:  18 Qxd6 Be6  19 Bg2 Qxg4  20 Be7 Re8  21 Rfe1 Nf3+  Amusingly, the computer still thinks White is fine here, but he didn't last much longer:  22 Bxf3 Qxf3   23 Qa3 Qb7   24 Bg5 Bf8   25 Rxe6? Rxe6  26 Qxa4 Re5   0 -1  Kasparov also mentions 18 Qd5 Be6  or 18 Bd5 Qb5, both good for Black. }
18. Rc1 Qb4
{ Stockfish prefers Bxg4 here and already claims a small Black edge.  Qb5 is also worth considering. }
19. a3
{ In Smyslov's '125 selected games', he gives this an exclamation mark, without explanation.  The computer is unimpressed, and slightly prefers Bg2 or Bd2.  Kasparov also gave it the exclam, while his computer back in the day liked 19 Be7, but after some careful prodding, changed its mind... }
19... Qxb2
{ Qb5 was possible, and maybe better.  Now White's light squared bishop should get out of Dodge - 20 Be4!  But instead... }
20. Qxa4 Bb7
{ This is almost a positional trap.  White can keep equality with Bxb7, or he can win the queen... }
21. Rb1
{ And he opts for the latter.  Unfortunately, this wasn't the time to go about overthrowing the monarchy.  Black's minor pieces are simply stronger than the queen here, and struggle as he might, Botvinnik is now lost.  He later said that despite 20 minutes thought he failed to find the "elementary" 21 Bxb7 Qxb7 22 Rc3 etc with a probable draw. }
21... Nf3+ 22. Kh1 Bxa8 { Avoiding Qxb1 23 Rxb1 Bxa8 24 Be7 } 23. Rxb2 Nxg5+
24. Kh2 Nf3+ 25. Kh3 Bxb2 26. Qxa7 Be4 27. a4 Kg7
{ A beautiful move, again, passed without comment is Smyslov's book.  He gets off the back rank in case of future rook lifts, nad is completely safe sharing the diagonal with his dark square bishop. He also has a sneaky threat:  h5!  For example, 28 a5? h5!  29 gh Rh8, splat! }
28. Rd1 Be5
{ Strong, But Ng5+ Kh2 h5 is even stronger.  Even so, Black is still completely winning  (+3 in computer speak)  . }
29. Qe7
{ Oops!  +5 now.  White had to play the horrible Kg2, but walking into discovered check is never going to be natural. }
29... Rc8 30. a5 Rc2
{ Threatening Rxf2-h2 mate, and if White plays Rf1 then Bd3.  So Kg2 is forced after all... }
31. Kg2 Nd4+ { Nd2+ is also extremely strong. } 32. Kf1 Bf3 33. Rb1
{ White could try 33 Re1 Bxg4  34 Rxe5!?  But Black shouldn't bite:  34... Nf3!!35 Kg2 Rc1 is the end. }
33... Nc6
{ The computer finds the amusing maneuver Nb3, idea Nd2, Bc6.  Smsylov finds the human Nc6, hitting the Queen and threatening Bd4  (and, as it happens Na5)  , forcing resignation. }
*

